figure_1.title: Figure 1.  Conceptual Demonstration of the Autoregressive Integrated Moving Average (ARIMA) Model.
figure_1.caption: The vertical blue dotted line indicates the onset of the COVID-19 pandemic.

figure_2.title: Figure 2.  Visit Rates by Treatment Type During the Prepandemic (March 2019 to February 2020) and Pandemic (March 2020 to February 2021) Periods.
figure_2.caption: A to C, Actual in-person, forecasted (counterfactual) in-person, and telemedicine visit rates for oral therapies (A), outpatient infusion treatments (B), and inpatient infusion treatments (C). The vertical blue dotted lines indicate the onset of the COVID-19 pandemic; shaded areas indicate the 95% prediction interval.

claims.sentence: Figure 1 demonstrates a conceptual model of the ARIMA method.
Months when the observed rates exceeded the 95% prediction interval (PI) surrounding the forecasted estimates were deemed to have been statistically significantly affected by the pandemic (Figure 1).

In-Person Visit Rates
Early pandemic months experienced significant reductions in in-person visit rates for oral therapy (March to May 2020) and outpatient infusions (April to May 2020) subgroups over all diseases combined (Figure 2).

The vertical blue dotted lines indicate the onset of the COVID-19 pandemic; shaded areas indicate the 95% prediction interval.When stratified by disease, patients with multiple myeloma had significant reductions within each treatment type (Figure 3).
During this period, in-person visit rates returned to close to nonpandemic rates for many diseases and treatment types (Figure 2 and eTables 4 and 5 in Supplement 1).
This trend persisted across all treatment types (Figure 2 and eTable 6 in Supplement 1).
